✅ Task: Compare Focus Bear with Other Productivity Apps
📌 Be completely honest in your evaluation—Focus Bear might not always be better than other tools, and that’s okay! The goal is to understand the competitive landscape and think critically about where Focus Bear stands.
📌 Research other productivity and focus apps such as:

Freedom
Cold Turkey
Tiimo
Routinery

📌 Then, reflect on the following questions:

What makes Focus Bear different from these apps?

Freedom and Cold Turkey function as purely distraction blockers - meaning thy are exceptional at blicking out websites and apps. However, that is essentially all they do. 
Tiimo and Routinery are primarily routine/schedule/habit setting apps. They help plan your routines and send reminder notifications. However, they seem less strict in terms of enforcing habits compared to Focus bear. 
Focus bear tends to encourage real-time habit engagement, rather than just gently reminding you to track your progress.

Overall, biggest difference with Focus Bear compared to all the others, is the focus on helping neurodivergent people specifically. It combimes 
active distraction blocking and routine guidance into one app, rather than focusing specifically on one aspect. 

If you were a user, why would you choose Focus Bear over competitors?

To reiterate the point made above:

If I was someone who has ADHD or struggle with executive function, I would find Focus Bear more suitable. The other apps is working with the assumption that I already have the discipline to properly use them. Therefore, it doesn't hold your hand in terms of guiding you.
I'd choose Focus Bear specifically if I already know that the other apps doesn't work for me as a user. It's for people who need more than a nudge- they need an app to strictly guide them when they don't have the willpower or natural ability to focus. 

What’s one feature that other apps have that Focus Bear doesn’t?

Compared to the other apps, Focus bear currrently lacks the ability to 
social engage with other users in a session/group setting. Specifically, it's currently very solo-focused. A potential problem with this is that having no external (social) motivation like sharing routines or competing in maintaining streaks could make for a very
isolating experience. The Focus Bear app can benefit from sharing acheivements or joining a group block; because for many ADHD people, having a buddy is considered a very effective focus strategy. 

Based on your research, what’s one improvement you think Focus Bear could make?

Right now, I found the onboarding flow a little overwhelming and confusing. During initial onboarding, you are presented with a 'blank' canvas of setting up your own habits and routines. 
However, this may seem very overwhelming to a user, due to a lack of proper onboarding process. You still have to design your routine - which sort of contradicts Focus Bear's ethos enforcing a strict routine. 

A potential improvement can be having a more clear and concise onboarding process, like a demonstration and walkthrough for all the features on the app. Potentially an AI bot can be used to help ask questions to help gauge an initial routine for you. Hence, you can have a 'starting kit' which you can adjust as you become more familiar with the interface. 
